-gated channels","Potassium efflux through delayed rectifier channels","Potassium influx through inward rectifier channels"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe rapid upstroke (Phase 0) of the cardiac action potential is caused by \u003Cstrong\u003Erapid sodium influx through voltage-gated channels\u003C/strong\u003E. When the membrane potential reaches threshold, voltage-gated sodium channels open suddenly, allowing rapid sodium entry which depolarizes the cell from about -90 mV to +20 mV in just a few milliseconds.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPotassium efflux through delayed rectifier channels\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs during repolarization (Phase 3)\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium influx through L-type channels\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs during the plateau phase (Phase 2)\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChloride efflux through chloride channels\u003C/strong\u003E - Chloride channels play a minor role in cardiac action potentials\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPotassium influx through inward rectifier channels\u003C/strong\u003E - These channels maintain the resting membrane potential (Phase 4)\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThis initial rapid sodium influx is essential as it triggers calcium release from the sarcoplasmic reticulum, initiating the excitation-contraction coupling process.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The rapid upstroke (Phase 0) of the cardiac action potential is caused by sudden sodium influx through voltage-gated sodium channels.","The initial rapid depolarization in cardiomyocytes is essential for triggering calcium release from the sarcoplasmic reticulum.","Fast sodium channels are the primary channels responsible for the initial depolarization in working cardiomyocytes."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Boron W. F., Boulpaep E. L. Medical Physiology. (3rd edition). US. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2017."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53422"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16953"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53422"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-08T12:10:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-08T12:11:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9643"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67957"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/a